🧠 Step 2 — HOW to Actually Contribute (Real Way)
❌ What beginners do (wrong)
Fork repo
Don’t understand anything
Try random code
✅ What YOU should do
Step 1: Understand the Project
Read README → Understand data → Run code locally
Step 2: Find Small Issues

Examples:

Fix incorrect SQL query
Improve data cleaning
Add missing null handling
Improve README
Add new analysis question
Step 3: Start Small Contributions

👉 Examples YOU can do:

Add new SQL queries
Improve existing queries
Add new insights
Fix data issues
Improve documentation
🔥 Step 3 — What You Should Contribute (Based on YOUR SKILLS)
💡 For Your Current Level

You can contribute:

✅ SQL Contributions
Optimize queries
Add new analysis queries
Fix aggregation mistakes
✅ Data Cleaning
Handle null values
Fix inconsistent data
Add transformations
✅ Analysis
Add new questions like:
Top 3 states per month
Trend analysis
Rate comparisons
✅ Documentation (VERY UNDERRATED)
Improve README
Add explanations
Add query descriptions

👉 This is HUGE for beginners

🧠 Step 4 — How to Make It Resume-Worthy

Don’t just say:

Contributed to open source ❌

Say:

• Contributed to open-source data analysis project by improving SQL queries and adding new analytical insights  
• Implemented data cleaning techniques and enhanced dataset quality  
• Collaborated through pull requests and code reviews on GitHub
🚀 Step 5 — Your FIRST Contribution Plan (Do This)
🔹 Option A (EASIEST + SMART)

👉 Take an existing repo and:

Add your COVID SQL queries
Improve README
Add insights section
🔹 Option B

👉 Find a repo and:

Add 1 new feature:
Top 3 states per month analysis
🔹 Option C

👉 Fix something:

Wrong aggregation
Missing null handling
Incorrect metric
🧠 Step 6 — How to Interact Like a Pro

When contributing:

✔ Open Issue
"I would like to work on improving SQL queries for better analysis"
✔ Pull Request

Explain:

What you changed  
Why you changed it  
What improvement it brings  
🔥 Reality Check
You don’t need to be expert to contribute
You need to be consistent and thoughtful
🧠 Final Strategy (BEST FOR YOU)
Do this:
Build your project (you are doing it) ✅
Upload to GitHub ✅
Improve it
Then:
Contribute similar improvements to other repos
🚀 One-Line Summary
Start small → understand project → add value → document clearly → repeat
